{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_0","type":"agent_message","text":"final_filename: p19.cir\n\nObjective: create a single-supply NMOS Gilbert cell mixer where the differential output voltage Voutp - Voutn is proportional to the product of the differential RF input Vrfp - Vrfn and the differential LO input Vlop - Vlon. The expected transient waveform should contain differential mixing products at the sum and difference frequencies of the checker-driven inputs, especially near 200 Hz and 2.2 kHz, with both products above 1 mV when measured from Voutp - Voutn.\n\nTopology: use a classic stacked NMOS Gilbert cell with a bottom differential RF transconductance pair, an upper LO switching quad, two 10 kOhm resistive loads to VDD, and an NMOS tail current source. VDD must be 5 V. The RF pair converts Vrfp - Vrfn into differential drain currents. The LO quad commutates those RF currents between the two load resistors so the output current polarity follows Vlop - Vlon, producing multiplication in the differential output.\n\nRequired devices:\nMtail: NMOS tail current source from source node tail_src to ground, drain at rf_tail, gate driven by a fixed bias Vbias_tail.\nMrfp: NMOS RF input transistor with gate Vrfp, drain rf_drp, source rf_tail, bulk tied to source rf_tail.\nMrfn: NMOS RF input transistor with gate Vrfn, drain rf_drn, source rf_tail, bulk tied to source rf_tail.\nMlo1: NMOS LO switch from Voutp to rf_drp, gate Vlop, bulk tied to source rf_drp.\nMlo2: NMOS LO switch from Voutn to rf_drp, gate Vlon, bulk tied to source rf_drp.\nMlo3: NMOS LO switch from Voutn to rf_drn, gate Vlop, bulk tied to source rf_drn.\nMlo4: NMOS LO switch from Voutp to rf_drn, gate Vlon, bulk tied to source rf_drn.\nRloadp: 10 kOhm from VDD to Voutp.\nRloadn: 10 kOhm from VDD to Voutn.\nIndependent sources must explicitly drive Vrfp, Vrfn, Vlop, and Vlon in the final netlist, even though the checker may detach and replace them. Include VDD and Vbias_tail sources. Use the specified NMOS model: Vth=0.7 V, kp=100u, W=50u, L=1u.\n\nBiasing assumptions: all NMOS bulks are tied to their local source nodes. The checker injects RF and LO signals around common-mode voltages, so the circuit must not depend on floating inputs. Choose nominal DC source definitions compatible with the task: Vrfp and Vrfn centered near 2.0 V with small opposite-phase 1 kHz signals; Vlop and Vlon centered around a LO common-mode suitable for switching, with opposite-phase 1.2 kHz signals. Tail bias should be threshold-aware, for example around 1.1 V to 1.3 V, so the tail source supplies moderate current without forcing the outputs to rails. The 10 kOhm loads should bias Voutp and Voutn near mid-supply for a useful LO common-mode sweep, leaving enough headroom for the stacked RF pair and LO quad.\n\nAnalysis: include `.tran 1u 5m`. The transient result should show Voutp and Voutn moving differentially around a mid-supply operating point rather than being stuck at VDD or ground. Verification should inspect `V(Voutp)-V(Voutn)` and confirm FFT content at the expected difference and sum frequencies: |1.2 kHz - 1 kHz| = 200 Hz and 1.2 kHz + 1 kHz = 2.2 kHz.\n\nOutput constraints: the final netlist must contain the exact input node names Vrfp, Vrfn, Vlop, Vlon and exact output node names Voutp, Voutn. It must be a flat SPICE netlist with explicit devices and sources, no subcircuits or hidden placeholders."}}
